TY  - JOUR
T1  - Exploring the Foundations of Cumulative Innovation: Implications for Organization Science
AU  - Murray, Fiona
AU  - O'Mahony, Siobhán
Y1  - 2007/12/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.1070.0325
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.1070.0325
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 1006
EP  - 1021
VL  - 18
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Organizational theorists have built a deep understanding of the conditions affecting knowledge sharing. However, for innovation to occur, knowledge must not just be shared, but also reused, recombined, and accumulated. Such accumulation is not inherent to the innovation process but can be either supported or limited by the context in which it occurs. We propose a framework arguing that three conditions shape this context: disclosure, access, and rewards. We show how these conditions operate at the institutional, field, community, and organizational levels. Our framework highlights how when innovators encounter barriers to the accumulation of knowledge, their solutions are often organizational ones rather than legal ones. This suggests an expanding terrain for organizational scholars interested in debates often dominated by law and economics.
AB  - Organizational theorists have built a deep understanding of the conditions affecting knowledge sharing. However, for innovation to occur, knowledge must not just be shared, but also reused, recombined, and accumulated. Such accumulation is not inherent to the innovation process but can be either supported or limited by the context in which it occurs. We propose a framework arguing that three conditions shape this context: disclosure, access, and rewards. We show how these conditions operate at the institutional, field, community, and organizational levels. Our framework highlights how when innovators encounter barriers to the accumulation of knowledge, their solutions are often organizational ones rather than legal ones. This suggests an expanding terrain for organizational scholars interested in debates often dominated by law and economics.
